<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  entitlements.plist — hardened-runtime entitlements for the v0 Tauri bundle
  (SI-6 packaging, M6). Applied by `tauri build` to BOTH the outer app and the
  aibender-core sidecar under `macOS.hardenedRuntime: true`.

  WHY THESE KEYS (measured, spike-e S7, docs/spikes/spike-e-signing-ant.md):
  the aibender-core sidecar is a Node/Bun-runtime binary. Under the hardened
  runtime (required for notarization) a JIT-using runtime is killed at launch
  unless it carries `allow-jit` + `allow-unsigned-executable-memory`. S7 proved
  these two keys sign cleanly and pass deep+strict verification even ad-hoc.

  v0 posture: signing is DRY-RUN (macOS.signingIdentity = null → ad-hoc / no
  signature). Local builds carry no quarantine bit, so Gatekeeper never assesses
  them and hardened-runtime entitlements cost nothing at launch. These keys are
  the notarization-READY shape for the day the owner runs the real Developer-ID
  path (docs/runbooks/release-packaging.md) — they are inert for local use.

  NO network, camera, mic, or file-access entitlements: the cockpit talks only
  to the loopback broker over a WebSocket (CSP-restricted) and reads the
  bootstrap file via its own command — there is no outbound-network entitlement
  to grant, and the sandbox is deliberately NOT enabled (a broker that spawns
  child CLIs cannot run under App Sandbox).
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
